I agree. Curry made watching basketball exciting for me again. The last time I was excited about watching basketball was in the 90's when the Bulls, led by Jordan, were creating their dynasty. Curry is without doubt one of the most skilled players to ever play, and definitely the most impactful on the game of basketball since Jordan. (Sorry Lebron James's devotees.) The sad thing is his greatness won't be widely appreciated until he's retired.   Note: Lebron James's devotees are always insecure when Curry's name is brought up, (and thus, lashing out) because in the last 10 years, the only real threat to Lebron's legacy has been Curry (not Durant, not Westbrook, not Leonard, not Harden.) This year's All-Star game was a reflection of the dichotomy that the two represent: Curry -- skill, handles, phenomenal shooting, and LeBron -- athleticism (allegedly by steroid use,) power and dominance. It's David vs Goliath, and quite the microcosm we each deal with. Curry is whom we relate to, in that hard work and the honing of one's skills will produce desired results; Lebron is the ideal, the myth, the one whom we wish we were, in that having his physique and athleticism, and therefore more power, provides us a way of glossing over any insecurity we may have or may face. (Thus, white boys fanboy over him the most.)   Curry is one of the greatest players in the league right now, and I'm sure that when his career's over, or at least nearing its end, he'll be one of the greatest players of all time.
